by /DC=ch/DC=cern/OU=Organic Units/OU=Users/CN=meloam/CN=692113/CN=Andrew Malone Melo</pre></div><div class='update_description'><i onclick="document.location='31878#1479246117'; reset_anchor();" class="pull-right icon icon-share"></i><div class="header"><time datetime="2016-11-15T21:41:57+00:00">Nov 15, 2016 09:41 PM UTC</time><a class="anchor" name="1479246117">&nbsp;</a></div><pre>Hi Mine,

We both agree that I control 3223.sc16.org and IEEE controls the next domain up. Your concern with granting me host certificates within 3223.sc16.org is that it somehow conflates that with the next higher domain.  Applying that logic would imply signing vanderbilt.edu conflates with edu? &#34;EDU&#34; doesn&#39;t have anything to do with CMS, yet people are allowed to sign certificates within subdomains inside &#34;.edu&#34;. I fail to see how one extra layer of domains changes things.

I understand that you have requirements on your side to prevent malicious uses of these certificates, but I really don&#39;t see your concern in this case. I control the domain, we paid good money for it, but I can&#39;t use it because there&#39;s an intermediate domain between the TLD and my domain?

Thanks,
Andrew

by /DC=ch/DC=cern/OU=Organic Units/OU=Users/CN=meloam/CN=692113/CN=Andrew Malone Melo</pre></div><div class='update_description'><i onclick="document.location='31878#1479245171'; reset_anchor();" class="pull-right icon icon-share"></i><div class="header"><time datetime="2016-11-15T21:26:11+00:00">Nov 15, 2016 09:26 PM UTC</time> by <b>Mine Altunay</b><a class="anchor" name="1479245171">&nbsp;</a></div><pre>Hi Andrew

I understand your situation and we all do our best to help you. Having said that we have a process in OSG to ensure our security.

Each VO has a list of authorized  domains, this list is kept at OIM. Then VOs can identify gridadmins who can request and approve certificate requests for their authorized domains.

Since sc16.org is not an authorized domain for cms, even if we grant you the GridAdmin privilege, you still won&#39;t be able to get a certificate. Before generating the cert, OIM will check your requested domain against the authorized domains for CMS and simply refuse this. This check is in place in case of a malicious grid admin makes requests outside of his domain, such as for bankofamerica.com which can be very dangerous for unsuspecting users.

We believe that you own the domain 3326.sc16.org, but the sc16.org is owned by the IEEE. And, this domain has not ties to CMS and I believe adding this domain really cuts it too close. It reminds me of hacking/phshing websites they try to imitate a legitimate site with awfully similar names and hoping unsuspecting users do not notice the difference, like  cnn.com.co or harward.com.

If we know about this request earlier, we may be able to find a solution in time, but given the very short timeline, I am afraid there is not much we can do.</pre></div><div class='update_description'><i onclick="document.location='31878#1479244215'; reset_anchor();" class="pull-right icon icon-share"></i><div class="header"><time datetime="2016-11-15T21:10:15+00:00">Nov 15, 2016 09:10 PM UTC</time><a class="anchor" name="1479244215">&nbsp;</a></div><pre>Hi all,

I unfortunately have to use *.3223.sc16.org because that&#39;s what the reverse DNS is for this IP range, and the OSG-provided client barfs&#58;

$ uberftp se20.accre.vanderbilt.edu -P 2812
220 se20.accre.vanderbilt.edu GridFTP Server 10.4 (gcc64, 1463669416-85) [Globus Toolkit 6.0] ready.
Failed to init security context
GSS Major Status&#58; Unexpected Gatekeeper or Service Name

GSS Minor Status Error Chain&#58;
globus_gsi_gssapi&#58; Authorization denied&#58; The expected name for the remote host (host@....) does not match the authenticated name of the remote host (se20.accre.vanderbilt.edu). This happens when the name in the host certificate does not match the information obtained from DNS and is often a DNS configuration problem.

$ uberftp b20.3223.sc16.org -P 2812
220 se20.accre.vanderbilt.edu GridFTP Server 10.4 (gcc64, 1463669416-85) [Globus Toolkit 6.0] ready.
Failed to init security context
GSS Major Status&#58; Unexpected Gatekeeper or Service Name

GSS Minor Status Error Chain&#58;
globus_gsi_gssapi&#58; Authorization denied&#58; The expected name for the remote host (host@....) does not match the authenticated name of the remote host (se20.accre.vanderbilt.edu). This happens when the name in the host certificate does not match the information obtained from DNS and is often a DNS configuration problem.

Jeny - Like I mentioned before, *.3223.sc16.org *is* owned by me. Would it work to sign certificates within that subdomain?

Thanks for everyone&#39;s help. It caught me by surprise that SC would be unable to change the reverse DNS resolution, so I&#39;m trying to find some way to actually do this demo so I don&#39;t have to go home with nothing to show for it.

Cheers,
Andrew

by /DC=ch/DC=cern/OU=Organic Units/OU=Users/CN=meloam/CN=692113/CN=Andrew Malone Melo</pre></div><div class='update_description'><i onclick="document.location='31878#1479243628'; reset_anchor();" class="pull-right icon icon-share"></i><div class="header"><time datetime="2016-11-15T21:00:28+00:00">Nov 15, 2016 09:00 PM UTC</time> by <b>Jeny Teheran</b><a class="anchor" name="1479243628">&nbsp;</a></div><pre>Alain,

The issue here is not the VO Andrew belongs to, but the domain where the hostnames for the machines are from.
I can see that Andrew is a GridAdmin for rednet.org and vanderbilt.edu domains (VO&#58;CMS). He certainly could submit certificate requests for hostnames within those domains and approve the requests by himself.

Andrew, any chance you can name your machines with hostnames within those domains and redirect requests to b2[0-6].3223.sc16.org?

We cannot approve the issuance of a host certificate with a hostname ending in &#34;.sc16.org&#34; domain because Andrew does not own the domain.
And more precisely, OIM won&#39;t allow the submission of a host certificate request in &#34;.sc16.org&#34; domain. Currently, it is not registered as a domain of any VO.

--
Jeny</pre></div><div class='update_description'><i onclick="document.location='31878#1479242375'; reset_anchor();" class="pull-right icon icon-share"></i><div class="header"><time datetime="2016-11-15T20:39:35+00:00">Nov 15, 2016 08:39 PM UTC</time> by <b>OSG RA</b><a class="anchor" name="1479242375">&nbsp;</a></div><pre>Security,

