by /DC=ch/DC=cern/OU=Organic Units/OU=Users/CN=meloam/CN=692113/CN=Andrew Malone Melo</pre></div><div class='update_description'><i onclick="document.location='31878#1479234371'; reset_anchor();" class="pull-right icon icon-share"></i><div class="header"><time datetime="2016-11-15T18:26:11+00:00">Nov 15, 2016 06:26 PM UTC</time> by <b>Mine Altunay</b><a class="anchor" name="1479234371">&nbsp;</a></div><pre>Hi

The normal procedure is to add the new domain to the OIM and then install the requestor as a gridadmin.

Before we add a domain to OIM, we must reasonably confirm that the domain indeed belongs to the requestor. This is to make sure that people can only manage domains that they own. Otherwise, anyone can get certificates for google.com or bankofamerica.com which is obviously a big security problem for our CA. If the person can show they own this domain and their ties to OSG, then we can add this domain. The easiest way to do this is to show DNS ownership or such.</pre></div><div class='update_description'><i onclick="document.location='31878#1479232147'; reset_anchor();" class="pull-right icon icon-share"></i><div class="header"><time datetime="2016-11-15T17:49:07+00:00">Nov 15, 2016 05:49 PM UTC</time> by <b>Anthony Tiradani</b><a class="anchor" name="1479232147">&nbsp;</a></div><pre>So what can we do for Andrew then?

Anthony Tiradani</pre></div><div class='update_description'><i onclick="document.location='31878#1479231964'; reset_anchor();" class="pull-right icon icon-share"></i><div class="header"><time datetime="2016-11-15T17:46:04+00:00">Nov 15, 2016 05:46 PM UTC</time> by <b>Jeny Teheran</b><a class="anchor" name="1479231964">&nbsp;</a></div><pre>A Grid Admin can only approve host certificates requests within the domain he is approved for.
At the time of submitting the request, it will fail because OIM checks whether the submitter is a GridAdmin who can requests certs within sc16.org.

